    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-08-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-08-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="328" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <head>No. 1041.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Winchester</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Berne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-08-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 17, 1888</date>.
                            (Received August 27.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 230.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Last year the congress of the institute of
                        international law took place at Heidelberg, and on the 30th of September
                        next it will be opened at Lausanne, the seat of the Swiss federal
                        tribunal.</p>
                <p>The list of subjects for discussion was selected at last year’s assembly and
                        comprises the common features of the conflict of civil laws; the conflict of
                        the laws relative to marriage and divorce; joint stock companies, and
                        encounters at sea. Then comes the law of extradition, international penal
                        law, the occupation of unclaimed territories according to the treaty of
                        Berlin; the international laws concerning railways, telegraphs, and
                        telephones in time of war; and finally, a question of vital importance for
                        Switzerland, in what manner and in what limits can governments exercise the
                        right of expulsion of strangers.</p>
                <p>I am etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Boyd Winchester.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
